rerum naturam: Lueretius uses natura in many different senses· Here and in 2 5 by natura rerum is meant what we often understand by ‘nature,’-the sum and system oi things existent; as Humboldt defines it (‘Cosmos,' tr. by Otte', Introd.): “Nature considered ra- trhnally, that is to say, submitted to the process oi thought, is a unity in diversity oi phenomena; a harmony, blending together oi all created things, however dissimilar in form and attributes; one great whole (rb πᾶν) animated with the breath oi lite.’' Oiten our poet personifies nature, regards her as a mysterious living presence, that “makes herself felt as a peculiar and independent power.” Cf. ’ especially 2, 1090-92: ‘It you keep in mind these things well thought out, nature untrammelled at once and iree from haughty masters is seen ot her own accord by herself without the power of the gods to do all things' The idea oi a will behind all movement is so firmly impressed upon the minds oi men that, strive as they may to believe in pure chance or necessity, they generally end by personi- iying something. Fate in antiquity was only a personification of natural law. It is a significant iact that materialists oi our own time often spell matter and evolution with capital letters. Evolution, a process, takes the place oi a deity, and matter is thought to contain the “promise and potency ot all terrestrial liie” (Tyndall). “It seems almost a matter oi taste whether we worship the masculine God, the feminine Nature, or the neuter All.” Lange, ‘Hish of Material- ism,’ tr. iii. 340. On Lucretius' conception oi Nature as a person· ality, see Ritter, ‘Hist oi Ancient Philosophy,’ Bohn's cd. iv. 87-88. Lucr. also uses the word natura to express ‘natural constitution' oi a thing, ‘substance' and the like.
